{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_perry_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600313/1930122801/0468.xml":{"full_text":"Editorial Page\ni\nPart 2\u2014B Page*\nDRAMATIC POLITICS LOOM\nIN NEW CONGRESS SESSION\nEvenly Matched Parties, on Eve of Ma\nneuvers Over Presidency, Have\nMany Issues to Fight Out.\nBT MARK SULLIVAN.\nTHE writer began this article in\nthe spirit of composing one of\nthose year-end annals\u2014summa\nries of the old year and forecasts\nof the new\u2014which many writers\nAnd other authorities will contribute to\nnearly all the newspapers and period\nicals during the coming week. It oc\ncurred to me, as a partial preparation,\nto look back through old newspaper files\nfor the similar summaries and forecasts\nin past periods of business depression\u2014\nthe depression of the early 1890 s, the\npanic of 1907 and its sequel, the busi\nness phenomena that followed the be\nginning of the Great War in 1915, and\nthe deflation depression of 1920 and\n1921.\nI knew what I should find, and I\nfound it \u2014a spirit of somber gloom on\nthe New Year day when the depression\nwas acute \u2014followed (in most cases) by\nnormal cheerfulness, or even elation, on\nthe New Year day of a year later.\nFor example, on January 1, 1908 (fol\nlowing the panic year 1907), the year\ntnd commentators emitted clouds of\niadness. One New York newspaper said\non January 1, 1908, that the year just\nended was the worst for the railroads\nin all their history. The condition of\nbusiness depression was accompanied\n(then as now, and always) by expres\nsions of social and political unrest. An\narticle in the New York Times of Jan\nuary 6, 1908, gave a conspicuous head\nline to \u201cThe Country\u2019s Wealth\u2014ls 99\nPer Cent of It in the Hands of 1 Per\nCent of the People?\u201d\nPossessore of Wealth.\n(This particular type of expression of\ndiscontent, or the condition that causes\nit, must have abated much during the\n23 years that have elapsed; the current\nform of the same question has changed\nthe ratio, and now asks: \u201cIs 90 per cent\nof the country\u2019s wealth in the hands of\n10 per cent ofsthe people?\u201d)\nThe only cheerfulness that appeared\nin the year-end summaries on January\n1, 1908, and nearby days, was artificial,\nforced. There were, as now. attempts at\nartificial respirations for the sick pa\ntient in the shape of reassuring plati\ntudes from persons highly placed in the\nbusiness and political world. The then\nSecretary of the Treasury, Leslie M.\nShaw of lowa (he still lives, at the age\nof 82; one may see him any day at the\nWardman Park Hotel in Washington),\nwas solicited during the year by the\nnewspapers of the day to cheer the coun\ntry by remarking, \u201cThere is no occasion\nfor alarm.\u201d\nOne of the utterances from distin\nguished men that speckled the news\npapers with synthetic cheerfulness at\nthe end of 1907 came from an excep\ntionally solid man, and he expressed a\ncharacteristically solid sentiment. Jacob\nH Schifl, a mighty man of finance in\nthe first decade of this century, asso\nciated with the firm of Kuhn. Loeb\nCo., uttered in the New York World for\nDecember 29, 1807. two months after\nthe panic of that yekr, a sentence that\nmight safely be duplicated as guidance\nfor today;\nStrength In Experience.\n\u201cWith the period of quietness through\nwhich we are to pass for some time,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Schiff, \"we shall emerge be\nfore long stronger and better equipped\nthan ever before.\u201d\n(Were Mr. Schiff alive today, I sus\npect he might duplicate for 1931 his\nforecast for 1908, saying that we are\nabout to pass through a period of quiet,\nfrom which \u201cwe shall emerge before\nlong stronger and better equipped than\never before.\u201d)\nJust as Mi*. Schiff foretold at the\nclose of 1907, so did it turn out. One\nfear later, January 1, 1909, the New\nYork Tribune welcomed the New Year\nin the familiar figure of an Infant, with\na headline that said:\nProsperity greets a shivering infant\nand recited that \"the dining rooms of\nthe big hotels indicated clearly the re\nturn of prosperity. In the fine year\nof 1908, recovery from the panic of 1907\nmade rapid progress\nBy a year later yet, as New Year\nday of 1910 approached, the country\nwas preoccupied not with depression\nbut with the opposite of depression;\nhigh prices were so much in the public\nmind that the New York World pub\nlished a symposium from eminent au\nthorities about the rising prices of\neverything, and the causes thereof.\nAll of which two-year cycle of de\npression followed by recovery, from\nJanuary 1, 1907. to January 1, 1909.\ncan be summed up by a glance at the\nBrice of the common stock of the\nnited States Steel Corporation on\nthree successive year-beginnings. In\nthe year of depression, 1907. the price\nwas almost exactly cut in half; during\nthe succeeding year of recovery, 1908,\nit more than doubled again;\nJanuary 1, 1907 50\nJanuary 1, 1908 26\nJanuary 1, 1909 53\nOvermuch of Prophecy.\nFrom those records of 22 and 23 years\nago, the inference about today, about\nthe year Just closing and the one about\nto begin, seems very plain. That infer\nence, the application to today can be\naccepted safely. Nevertheless. I refrain\nfrom prophecy. I refrain, for one rea\nson among several, because there has\nalways been overmuch of it \u2014and I an\nticipate there will be more during the\nWorld Is Pervaded by Calcium Cloud,\nObservations W ith Spectroscope Reveal\nThe whole universe appears to be\npervaded by a cloud of calcium\u2014ex\ntending through all space with a dens\nity about one ten-billionth that of the\nearth\u2019s atmosphere.\nThis cloud, one of the latest mys\nteries of astronomy, is revealed by\nobservations with the spectroscope, j\naccording to Prof. E. A. Milne of Ox\nford University. Calcium lines, he says,\n\u2022re obtained In the spectra of the hot\nteat stars, where, because of the Intense\nheat, the calcium atoms would be so\nstripped of their electrons that 6uch\nlines would not be produced.\nThe explanation is that the calcium\nproducing these lines must be some\nwhere between the observed star and\nthe observer on earth rather than in\nthe star. Prof. Milne says. Furthermore,\nthey appear strongest in the spectra of\nthe moat distant stars. The lines of\n\u202211 the elements weaken with the dis\ntance of the source of light. So the\ncalcium cannot be In the star. It must\nbe In apace.\nAnalysis of the spectra, Milne ex\nplains, shows that the velocity of the\ncalcium la not that of the observed\n\u2022tar, but approximately that of the sun\nand Its planets through the galaxy.\nIn other words, It la not moving but\nthe earth Is.\nThe origin of this all-pervading\ncloud. Milne explains, probably Is due\nto the tremendous rpdiatlon pressure\noutward from the hottest stars, pushing\ncalcium atoms Into space. There Is a\ncalcium cloud about the sun, due alio\nw-\ncoming week. I suspect the country is\n\u201cfed up\u201d with it. The best quip I have\nf heard lately was passed on to me by\none who said it originated with Albert\nLasker, advertising agent and business\n1 man. Mr. Lasker is reputed to have\nsaid, \u201cWhat the country is suffering\n1 from is overprediction.\u201d (Will the\ntypesetter please be very careful with\nthat word.)\nI refrain from prediction for the fur\nther reason that prophecy is always\n1 risky. If the public men who are fre\nquently quoted in the press, as well as\nthe professional writers who contribute\nto the press (including the present one)\nwere to be confronted by the numerous\nand various prophecies and predictions,\nexpressed or implied, that they have\nuttered in past years, they would in\nmost cases have an experience likely to\ndiminish their self-confidence.\nFor example: After there had been a\nyear of panic and low prices in 1907\nand after there had been two years of\nrising prices in 1908 and 1909, and as\nthe end of 1909 approached and the\nNew York World printed its symposium\nfrom distinguished men about the causes\nof rising prices, one of those who con\ntributed was William E. Borah, eminent\nthen and eminent still. Senator Borah\ndelivered a judgment: \u201cWe seem to be\napproaching a time when we shall be\nimporting (foodstuffs). This is due to\nthe failure to fertilize and keep up the\nproducing power of our lands and the\nfailure to utilize the 25,000,000 acres of\narid land in the West.\u201d\nJudgment of Today.\nThat was 21 years ago. Today the\ncommon judgment seems to be that\nAmerica produces not too little food\nstuffs but too much; that what we need\n1s not more acres of production, but\nfewer\u2014and the counsel given to farm\ners is that they should restrict their\nacreage.\nSo much for all that. As to the po\nlitical aspects of the year just opening,\nsome definite tnings can be said. In\none sense it will be, so to speak, a non\npolitical year; there will be no national\nelection, no election of a President, no\ngeneral election of Representatives to\nCongress or of Senators.\nThere will be. of course, sporadic spe\ncial elections to fill vacancies arising\nthrough death in both chambers of\nCongress. As it happens, these special\nelections will be particularly exciting.\nThey will be important because, with\neach death and its choice of a succes\nsor, the hair-line majority that exists\nin each of the two Houses will often\npass back and forth from Republican to\nDemocratic, or vice versa.\nWe can say of the new Congress\nelected on November 4 last that in both\nits chambers the parties are almost ex\nactly divided. It is an unusual condi\ntion, certain to be productive of excit\ning politics. We may say loosely, for\nthe present purpose, that the new Sen\nate which comes into existence next\nyear is Republican by a majority of one\nor two out of a total of 96. and that the\nnew House is Republican or Democratic\n(depending upon how contests turn\nout) by one or two. If that is the con\ndition as of today, it will be changed\nperhaps a dozen times during the com\ning year by the deaths of Senators and\nRepresentatives, depending upon wheth\ner the deaths occur among Republicans\nor among Democrats, and depending\nalso upon whether the successors chosen\nbelong to the same parties as the men\ndeceased.\nPossible G. O. P. Reverses.\nIn this shifting of the party majority\nfortune is likely to run against the Re\npublicans slightly. The reason, as re\nspects the Senate, is that when a Senator\ndies his successor is commonly chosen\nby the Governor of the State, and a good\nmany Governors are Democrats. To il\nlustrate by an example which we all\nhope will not be real, if either of the\ntwo Republican Senators from Connecti\ncut should die during 1931, his successor\nwill be chosen by a Democratic Governor.\nSimilarly, if the one Republican Senator\nfrom Ohio, or the one from Maryland,\nor the one from each of some other\nStates should die. his successor would\nbe chosen by a Democratic Governor.\nConsequently, as respects the Senate, the\nnet result of changes due to death is\nlikely to be adverse to the Republicans.\nTo look at the coming political year\nfrom another point of view\u2019; The Con\ngress now in session (which is the old\nCongress) will function until March 4\nnext and then will cease to exist. There\nafter, for nine quiet months, we shall\nhave no Congress whatever in Washing\nton. That is. we shall have no Congress\nunless there should be a special session\nof the new one. and it is now almost\ncertain there will be no special session\nThen, on December 7 next year, the new\nCongress 'will come into existence, the\nCongress in w hich both Houses of which\nthe parties are so evenly divided\nBecause of that fact the politics of\nthe new Congress will be dramatic. It\nwill be important for another reason:\nDecember of next year, when the new\nCongress meets, will be the eve of those\nmaneuvers of politicians whereby one\nman is chosen to be the presidential\ncand date of the Republican party and\nanother of the Democratic party.\nAnd that brings us back where we\nstarted, for the outcome of the presiden\ntial situation in 1932, as respects both\nthe nominations and the election, will\ndepend very largely upon the state of\nbusiness during the year just ahead of us\nto this pressure of light, but the force\n1 from a medium-hot star such as the\nsun is not sufficient to shove the atoms\ninto outer space. This can happen\nonly with the very hot stars.\nFrom the latter. Milne explains, there\nmust be a constant \u201cupward rain\u201d of\ncalcium atoms on an enormous scale\nThese become diffused in space and\nmake up the cosmic cloud.\nJapanese Labor Parly\nOusts Three Leaders\nThe Ronoto, or Labor-Farm party, one\nof the three outstanding proletarian po\nlitical groups, expelled three of its fore\nmost members recently. This summary\naction, taken against Dr. Hajime Kawa\nkaml, Susumu Kamimura and Kanjl\nShlndo. resulted from an article advo\ncating dissolution of the party which\nappeared in the party publication. The\nExecutive Committee voted almost unan\nimously to expel the three leaders, but\nonly after a heated discussion and after\nthe three men had steadfastly refused\nto retract. Dr. Kawakami was one of\nthe organisers of the Labor-Farm party\nFormerly he was a professor of political\ni science at the Tokio Imperial University.\nbut resigned four years ago, following\ncriticism of his views, which accompa\nl nied the discovery of an alleged Com\nmunist plot among a group of student*.\nEDITORIAL SECTION\nfflic Jsundaij ptsf.\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, DECEMBER 28; 1930.\nKeeping Workers on the Job\nEmployers Have Come to Realize Their Responsibility in Keeping Wheels of Progress Turning.\nBY ROBERT P. LAMONT,\nSecretary of Commerce of the United States.\nRECENTLY the head of one of the\ncountry\u2019s great industrial cor\nporations addressed a gathering\nof business men in New York.\nThe speaker was a man who\nhad conducted a vast business prosper\nously over a long period of years. He\ntalked nearly an hour and throughout\nthe time had the attention of practi\ncally every man in the audience. After\nhis address he was asked dozens of\nquestions.\nNeither the address nor the questions\nrelated to the making of profits. In\nstead, they related to the making of\njobs! It was plainly apparent that\nevery employer in the room was in\ntensely interested in learning how to\nkeep working forces intact.\nThe industrial leader who made the\naddress described the plan that his\ncompany had adopted several years be\nfore. It was a plan not to maintain or\nincrease profits, but to keep on the pay\n\u2014Prom a painting by Albertlne Randall Wheelan\n\u201cRIDE \u2019IM, COWBOY1\"\nroll In times of poor business all the\nmany thousands of men and women\nwhose names appeared on It In times\nof good business. He summarized the\nresult of that effort by stating that only\nHave You Right to Be Alive?\nEvery One Should Prove His Right to Live, as Man Never Gets Above Work, Sloan\u2019s Qafml\nBY IRVING BACHELLER.\nMATT SLOAN, so he Is called by\nhis Intimates, is, like Owen-\nYoung. an epic figure In Amer\nican life. In certain of the\nbasic elements of his char\nacter he reminds me of Young. Both\nwere rooted in a like soil out of which\ncame a deep and lasting respect for all\nthe great verities They are devoted\nto the same ideal of public service.\nAs a human product Sloan has long\nengaged my interest. I knew him when\nhe was finding his way to the eminent\nposition he now holds\u2014captain of the\nimmense industry of giving light and\nheat to the greatest municipality on this\ncontinent. He had come to an institu\ntion in Greater New York. He saw that\nits first need was honesty. He began to\nsearch his memory for honest men with\nwhom to surround himself. He found\nfirst one and then another, and called\nthem to his aid. His company began to\ngrow in power, efficiency and public\nesteem.\nBorn in Mobile, he has the courtesy\nof the old South. It is in his greeting, i\nhis smile, his cheerful good nature, hi.>\nmanner of disagreeing with one.\nA big industry is in some degree like\na ship. The ship may look as hand- j\nsome as ever when her bottom is cov-\nered with barnacles, but she has lost a\npart of her efficiency. Sloan will have i\na c\u2019ean ship above and below the line\nof visibility The pathway of a great\nenterprise is probably as full of hidden I\nenemies and perils as the salt sea.\nMan in Love With His Job.\nMatt Sloan is one of the bus.est men\nI know. Yet I have never met a happier\nperson. Stalwart, athletic, Blue-eyed.\nnearly 6 feet tall, his happiness bursts j\ninto laughter on slight provocation.\n\"You look like a man in love with his\nJob,\u201d I said, as our talk began.\n\"I am,\u201d he answered. \u201cThe big thing\nin life is to find your job and fall in\nlove with it. Then you must have the\nright kind of help. lam always looking\nfor honest, healthy, keen-minded young\nmen and women who want to work\nThe best of them can look forward tc\nbig salaries if they will only work hard.\u2019\n\"What is the great problem of Amer\nica?\u201d I asked.\nWithout a moment's hesitation he an\nswered\n\u201cHere are three great forces which are\nto continue the work of civilization.\nThey are government, business, the host\nof young.\n\"Business has grown to be immense\nand far-reaching. It Is a complicated\nand highly organized machine. The\nworld has never seen the like of it.\nNight and day it is moving. lus work\nnever ceases. It can accommodate a\ngreat variety of talents It needs a vast\narmy of helpers. It forces upon our\ngovernment a multitude of new prob\nlems. These great structures must de\npend absolutely on the honor, skill and\ndevotion of those who are to follow us.\nP\n16 people had been dropped from the\ncompany's pay roll since January 1,\n1930.\nAfter the meeting was over, this em\nployer of thousands was approached by\nMATTHEW 8. SLOAN.\n\u201cSo I answer that our great problem\nis the ho6t of young who are able to do\nthe work of the future. If our country\nis to prosper and be happy, some one\nhas got to do its work.\u201d\n\"Why not teach the young how to get\nrich and be above work?\u201d I asked.\n\u201cWell, you'd have to teach them also\nhow to get along without food and\nclothing and how to grow fur on the\nbody and live in caves. That old no\none of those who had listened to him\u2014\na man none too prosperous in appear\nance\u2014who introduced himself as a\nbuilder. He said, \u201cI Just want to thank\nyou for making me feel that maybe I\u2019m\ntion of getting above work is exploded.\nA man never gets above work. The\nfact is work gets above him. Since the\nbootlegger and the racketeer have been\nable to amass fortunes, wealth has\nceased to be impressive as a token of\nmanhood. A good American may well\nbe appalled by all the things that need\nto be done. Today every one should\nprove his right to be alive. Really. X\n1\nnot such a fool after all. I haven\u2019t\nfired a man myself in the last 12\nmonths; been keeping them working\nmost of the time on any kind of repair\nor construction job I could locate,\nwhether there was any profit in it or\nnot, and without making a nickel for\nmyself. Just lately I\u2019ve been wondering\nwhether I wasn\u2019t a fool and whether\nI oughtn\u2019t to just close down until\nthings pick up. But I feel now, after\nlistening to you, that I\u2019ve been doing\nthe right thing, after all.\u201d\nAnd that\u2019s the present attitude of\nthousands of business men, big and\nlittle, the country over. Here in the\nDepartment of Commerce at Washing\nton Col. Arthur Woods, chairman of\nthe President\u2019s Emergency Committee\nfor Employment, is getting reports from\nindustries of every kind and size dem\nonstrating conclusively that business\nmen are readily assuming what they\nbelieve to be their responsibilities to\nward their employes during the depres\nsion.\nThose reports contain nothing to In\ndicate that these men consider theii\nobligation to maintain employment or\ni wage payments as one of charitable\nz duty. Instead, their attitude Is that\ni (Continued on Fourth Page.)\nquestion if a healthy idler has any\nmoral right to be alive.\u201d\n\"I can tell you one thing that the\nworld wants to know,\u201d I said. \u201cHow\nare the young to be prepared to pass\nyour examination in the three requi\nsites of honesty, love of work and keen\nmindedness?\u201d\nSays Job Must Begin at Home.\n\u201cNaturally, the great job must begin\nat home,\u201d he said. \"It begins with the\ndifficult problem of making boys and\ngirls honest. That\u2019s the first thing to\nbe learned. If you don\u2019t get it at home,\nyou may have to live without it\u2014the\nworst handicap known to man. How\nare we going to teach honesty? Well,\nwe should begin before the student is\nborn. We should be honest ourselves\nand give him a proper inheritance. If\nyou were not honest before the child\nis born, get honest as soon as possible\nafter his arrival, or you will find him\nhard to live with. There is no detec\ntive in the world who will learn the\ntruth about you so quickly as your chil\ndren They hear all the gossip of the\nneighborhood. You cannot fool them.\nDon\u2019t allow yourself to think that you\ncan make a slip and get away with it,\nor that any part of your reputation is\nunknown to them. The frank little bar\nbarians with whom they associate do\nnot whisper. They yell. If you have\nthe habit of cheating in business or\nplaying with chorus girls, every kid in\nyour neighborhood will know it.\n\u201cNow, I suppose that the two people\nwho have the greatest power in them\nfor good or evil are the mother and\nthe father. Your child longs to honor\nyou. The greatest tragedy of childhood\ncomes when the idol is broken.\nTeaching of Honesty Stressed.\n\"A worthy example at home is the\nbig thing in teaching honesty. In\nschool I would say it is personality\nin the teachers and associates. Our\nschool boards demand from their teach\ners scholarship and what is called good\ncharacter. They may have all that and\nnot have personality, which includes a\ncapacity for leadership The young\nlong for and demand leadership. They\nwant a captain\u2014a hero. The teacher\nshould have a loving interest in them\nand a Joy in their companionship. Such\na one may have undying influence on\nthe minds of the young. He should be\nthe creator of lasting and beloved mem\nories Far greater than the scholarship\nto be got from a teacher is this subtle\nthing that comes from his personality,\nbecause it makes character.\n\u201cIn building that, we are apt to for\nget the power of advertising. We\ngrown-ups know that the love of honor\nand truth and work is the beginning of\nwisdom. How are we to sell it to the\nyoung? Just as we sell every other good\nthing, I would say\u2014by persistently ad\nvertlsing its merits, not in a humdrum,\n(Oontfajued on Fourth Pago.)\nSpecial Articles\nEUROPEAN LEADERS TURN\nFROM POLITICS TO TRADE\nStatesmen Hope for Improvement in\nInternational Affairs Through Bet\ntering of Economic Factors.\nBT FRANK H. SIMONDS.\nLONDON.\u2014 The coming of the holi\nday seasoq and the approach of\na new year must Inevitably In\nspire certain speculations as to\nthe prospects for the next 12\nmonths In foreign affairs. The year\nthat is ending has patently been the\nworst since the termination of the\nWorld War, and has unmistakably\naroused certain natural and even in\nevitable apprehensions. What, then, is\nthe outlook for a new year?\nThe answer to this interrogation must\nin no small measure be sought in the\neconomic rather than the political pros\npects. For in no small measure the\nexplanation of current political trouble\nis to be discovered in business depres\nsion. In the United States and Great\nBritain, which have known hard times,\nas in France, which has largely escaped\nthem, the political regime cannot be\nendangered by hard times. The United\nStates, for example, takes its grouch\nout upon the party in power, but no one\nwould for a moment think of abandon\ning the republican form of government\nbecause of stock market crashes and\nagricultural disaster.\nNew Governments Experimental.\nIn Europe, by contrast, the political\ninstitutions of many ooun tries \u2014and\namong them several of the most impor\ntant\u2014have as yet sent down only very\nshort roots. In Germany and Italy\nnotably the republic on the one hand\nand the Fascist state on the other repre\nsent novel experiments\u2014experiments\nwhich were entered upon contrary to\nthe will or without the participation of\nmajorities. Thus the permanence of\nthese forms of government depends al\nmost uniquely upon their ability to\nproduce prosperity at home and pres\ntige abroad.\nAnd particularly in the case of Ger\nmany economic depression following the\ndisaster of a lost war has made both\nachievements for the moment impossi\nble. More than a decade after the clcee\nof the war the German people find\nthemselves still lacking any semblance\nof pre-war prosperity at home, while\nthe republic has not regained the old\nposition of the empire abroad. Bread\nand glory are alike absent; hence the\nphenomenon of Hitler and the \u201cNazis.\"\nAnd in Italy, where the economic de\npression is severe, the necessity to em\nphasize international influence explains\nthe worst of the Mussolini thunderings.\nYet at bottom nothing is clearer than\nthat neither the Italian nor the Ger\nman Fascists desire war. We have\nslipped back easily and naturally into\nthe discussion of post-war European\ncircumstances in the language of pre\nwar times, but there is one essentially\ndifferent circumstance, namely, the fact\nthat all peoples have now known war,\nwhile in 1914 it was something outside\nthe experience not merely of the young\nbut also of the mature.\nIf there had been no far-reaching\nand intense economic crisis, it is fair\nto conclude that in the past two years\nwe should have heard comparatively\nlittle of the super-nationalistic bom\nbast of recent months. If there is even\na slight recovery in business, it is\nequally reasonable to believe that next\nyear will find international trade cir\ncumstances pushing international con\nflict possibilities off the front page.\nOne can support such statements by\na glance at still recent history. Fol\nlowing the making of peace from 1919\nj right down to the beginning of 1924\nI economic conditions in many countries\nafter a momentary recovery continued\nbad, and in the same period the inter\nnational relations moved with ominous\nsteadiness toward that supreme disas\nter that was the occupation of the Ruhr.\nAt that moment the ruin of Europe\nthat was forecast by many and escape\nfrom general misfortune seemed im\npossible.\nCatastrophe Brought Locarno.\nYet the very fact of having been\nbrought face to face with a new and\ngeneral catastrophe proved in the end\na salvation, for it opened the eyes of\nmillions who knew what war meant to\nthe dominating necessity for change.\nAnd in one brief 12 months we had the\nBritish and French elections and the\narrival of new men who made the\nDawes plan and after Innumerable\nconversations in many capitals met and\nmade history at Locarno. And after\nLocarno for four years Europe talked\npeace, co-operation, and, above all,\nbusiness.\nManifestly affairs have reached a\nsimilar crisis now. To go on in the\ndirection of the past year for another\n12 months is already perceived every\nwhere to be dangerous beyond exag\ngeration. Not dangerous in the sense\nof threatening a new war in any imme\ndiate time. The peril is not here. But\ndangerous in that peoples are drifting\ninto uncompromising support of posi\ntions of nationalistic purposes, which\nmust prevent present co-operation and\nGossip, Theft, Murder and Illness\nUnknown in Gumushane, Turkey\n\u2022r*.\nGUMUSHANE, Turkey \u2014Go6Sip, rob\nbery and murder are unknown in the\ncity of Gumushane and its surrounding\nvillages. Doors are never locked, not\neven at night, and the shop owners\nmeander to the coffee house in peace\nand leave their goods to the kind care\nof Allah on high. If any one drops his\npocketbook in the streets he need not\nworry and rush to the police station; he\nwill be sure that a passerby will run\nafter him and hand him his purse with\nnot a piaster missing.\nIn he village of Osduk the inhabit\nants have not stepped into a law court\nnot even as witnesses, for a period of\n40 years. The women of Gumushane\ndo not wander to their next door neigh\nbors to indulge in the indoor sport of\ngossiping. Heads do not come close to\nlattices and spy on the activities of\npassersby. Here the women are busy\nworking in the fields, picking fruits, es\npecially apples, and sorting them for\nmarket. They have neither the time\nnor the desire to tear people to pieces\nwith their tongues.\nGumushane Is the true paradise of\nTurkey, where doctors and druggists\ncannot earn a living. It has been esti\nmated that only $250 a year was spent\non medicine, due to the excellence of\nthe air and water. The druggists began\nto starve and were obliged to close shop.\nThe municipality opened a drug store,\nbut later this, too, was closed, and now\nthere is not a chemist in the whole city\nnor the need of one. The people of\nGumushane have proved that the saying\n\"an apple a day keeps the doctor away\u201d\nis a true one. Every field is full of\napple trees loaded with luscious fruit,\nand any one can go and eat his fill and\npick to his heart's content the big,\nround apples for a modest sum of money.\nHence children munch apples all day\nlong, and their rosy cheeks*** the envy\nof a great many wealthy parents in\nTurkey.\nTo recompense these people who\nneither gossip, lie nor kill. Allala has\ngiven fertile soil and plenty. AMti i\ncan hardly end other than in eventual\nconflict.\nThe question in Europe today is not\nbetween war or peace this year or .next\nThe problem is not averting some n\u00abw\nconflict Just around the comer. Tha\nreal problem is to organize peace, to\nestablish a system of international re\nlations which shall eliminate the sense\nof insecurity on the one hand and of\nintolerable inferiority on the other.\nAnd pessimism in and out of Europe in\nrecent months has arisen, not because\nany reasonable person believed France\nand Italy or Germany and Poland would\nexplode into war soon, but because no\none could fall to perceive that the\nquestions dividing the two sets of coun\ntries might one day end by precipitat\ning conflict, and in the meantime must\nblock the hope of establishing normal\nconditions.\nComing Year Critical.\nThe year which is coming will be, in\nmy Judgment, more critical than any\nother year since 1924. To say this is\nnot to imply that the crisis will not be\nmet. On the contrary, if one looks be\nlow the surface in Europe, it is mani\nfest that once more, as in 1924, large\ngroups of thoughtful men and women\nin every country are sufficiently dis\nquieted to insure activity. This is the\ncase in Germany, where the Hitler vic\ntory and its immediate international\nreprecussions have constituted a mani\nfest warning. It is true in Britain,\nwhere the blunders of MacDonald in\ninviting the Franco-Italian clash\nthrough mismanagement of the London\nNaval Conference, along with total fail\nure in handling domestic economic\nproblems, insures an early fall of the\nLabor government. It is true in France,\nwhere, so far, the nationalistic cam\npaign against Briand has failed. Eu\nrope has been for more than 12 months\ntalking politics, because it has been\nunable to do business. Interminable\nconversation has inevitably served to\nexacerbate international issues, which\nare always difficult. But this discus\nsion has ended by producing universal\nalarm. Now, if only there can be even\na moderate economic change; if, for\nexample, the German republic can only\nhave one or two favorable breaks\u2014\nwhich in the nature of things must\ncome on the business side \u2014the phe\nnomenon of Hitler may easily prove as\nevanescent as that of Boulanger, who\nflourished following the French disas\nters of 1870 under circumstances quite\nlike those which have given Hitler his\nvogue.\nIf Europe can only have better busi\nness and fewer conferences during the\nnext year, the end of 1931 is bound to\nbe more cheerful. One of the most\nunfortunate of the post-war develop\nments has been the politicians\u2019 growing\ninclination to try to avoid domestic\ntroubles by staging international con\nclaves. But in the present world situa\ntion the result is invariably to make\ntrouble abroad without doing good at\nhome. Conferences thus called an in\nevitably poorly prepared, badly con\nducted by statesmen whose main con\ncern at all moments must be for their\nhome front. Thus, while at London\nMacDonald was trying to fortify his\nparliamentary situation he found him\nself faced with an ever-growing Franco-\nItalian quarrel, which ended by setting\nEurope by the ears.\nWeary of Conferences.\nPeace through prosperity and with\nout conferences\u2014that was the recipe ol\none of the wisest of the old-style Euro\npean statesmen whom I encountered\nduring the London conference. Having\ntried all manner of conferences In the\npresent year, Europe is manifestly\nweary of the present method, and for\nthe moment even the politicians are\nbeginning to see .that it does not solve\ntheir domestic riddles. Wherefore it is\nmy own conviction that Europe will in\n1931 talk a great deal more about busi\nness than about politics, that even\nhereditary enemies like France and Ger\nmany will resume the exploration ol\npathways opened at Locarno and\nThoiry, and, above all, that a Tory gov\nernment coming to power in Britain\nwill impose a solution of the Franco-\nItalian naval rivalry in the Mediterra\nnean, a course impossible for Labor,\nbecause of its dislike of France and Its\nhatred of Fascism.\nIn sum, I believe that next year will\nsee a real Improvement in political con\nditions and international relations in\nEurope, subject only to the condition\nthat there be even a moderate business\nrevival. No one can exaggerate the\nchange in temper, spirit, purpose, in\nGermany between 1923, which was the\nyear of inflation and the occupation of\nthe Ruhr, and 1925, which saw stabili\nzation achieved and Locarno ratified.\nThen and now the European situation\ncentered in Germany, and then the\nchange in German feeling transformed\nthe whole Continental situation. Why\nshould it not happen again?\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nand pears sell 20 cents per 10 pounds,\nand meat is about 10 cents the pound.\nThe best butter is 30 cents a pound.\nThe fruit of Gumushane is shipped tfi\ngreat quantities to Istanbul and other\ncities of Turkey. But the same apples\nare sold for 20 cents a pound in Istan\nbul. This tremendous Increase in price\nis due to the lack of transportation.\nThe lack of transportation has been\none of the main sources of Turkey\u2019s\ntrouble. Although the soil of Turkey is\nfertile and fruits and vegetables are\nabundant, these could not be shipped\nout of the villages and cities in which\nthey grew. Hence the peasants only\nsowed or grew enough fruits to satisfy\nhome consumption. If they produced\nmore, the goods remained on their hands\nand rotted. The republic has realized\nthis great drawback and is trying to\nhelp the peasants to market their prod\nucts. Every year, thanks to Xsmet\nPasha's efforts, the various cities of\nTurkey are being linked with one an\nother by railroads, and a day will come\nwhen Turkey, too, will have trains\nequipped with refrigerators and ship\nmeat, fruit and vegetables from one end\nof the country to the other, Just as\nAmerica has succeeded in doing.\nOntario Road Earns\n$850,000 Within Year\nAn estimated profit of $850,000 was\nmade by the Temlskaming A North\nern Ontario railway for the year end\ned October 31, 1930. A check for; this\namount has been sent to Ontario, own\ner of the railway. The year Just end\ned is regarded as one of the most suc\ncessful in the history of the Temls\nkaming Northern Ontario railway,-\nwhich is administered by a provincial\ncommission and operates 500 miles of\nrailway in Northern Ontario and is be\ning rapidly expanded to MooM Fac\ntory, on James Bay.","height":"25338","width":"19716"}}
